Yes, I froze my cakes a couple of days earlier. I wrapped them in Glad Wrap and aluminum foil. I defrosted without unwrapping (to prevent condensation on the layers). So go ahead and freeze your cake layers. By the way I've frozen cake layers for a whole year with no ill effect, in fact many guests at the party said it was the best cake they ever ate in their lifves and they could not believe it had been frozen for an entire year. Just be sure to wrap your layers properly

Rating: 4
I finally had a fitting occasion to make this very expensive cake($35 for the ingredients without including the cost of amaretto). I made my own almond paste rather than using store bought. I also substituted almond oil for extract, using only one fourth the amount since it is much stronger. My filling looked nothing like the photos in the magazaine which shows dollops of filling. Mine was like a thick custard which poured onto the layers. I was a little short on eggs so I rounded up the amount of eggs with egg yolks, but I don't think that would have contributed to the consistency of the filling. To compensate for the runny texture I chilled each layer as I constructed the cake. To the frosting I added a tablespoon of Amaretto to give the frosting another layer of flavor. As another reviewer noted the cakes do squash down with the weight. My cake did not look as high as the one in the photo. This cake was a great hit. I saved a piece for myself which I ate the following day. The frosting tasted like really good cheesecake! The cake improved with age and I would consider putting this cake together a day early. I might adapt the frosting to make a cheesecake with almond crust and using the raspberry preserves as a topping under the berries. The berries make the cake, be sure to include enough of them with every slice. I didn't have any currant jelly on hand to glaze the berries which really didn't matter.

